First, I had to se the window size and the axises. The window variable was used to do so as well as seq_one and seq_two were used to set the axis as the original gene and the BLAST gene found. In [10]:
window = 3
seq_one = str(GSK3B_gene_seq)
seq_two = str(BLAST_Hit)
data = [
    [
        (seq_one[i : i + window] != seq_two[j: j + window])
        for j in range(len(seq_one) - window)
    ]
    for i in range(len(seq_two) - window)
]

print(data)

In this instance, we were unable to do this part as well but I learned how to fully completed the heat map. Firstly, the pairwise sequence heatmap was defined through creating a nested for loop in which doing a pairwise alignment was possible for each pair of kinases. The for loop first loops over the kinases and then does it again to go over all kinases. Then, the two sequences, variables X and Y, were aligned using .seq function with brackets to set them as the axises in heatmap and make sure they are properly aligned. Furthermore, then I initialize the int function set to my_numpy_array[i,j] with the brackets there to represent the for loop statements. In doing so, I got a list of the global alignments of the two sequences. By doing so, I was able to set no gaps and no parameters. Then used the return command to return what had just been globally aligned. Then, I set that created plot to the variable My_alignment_Scores to check that the matrix had been created through the for loop. Once that is all finished, the ploit can be created. First, a subplot was made using plt.subplots() function. Then, the axises were set to be present while constructing the heatmap. Lastly, plt.show() enabled the plot to be displayed.

In [19]:
def pairwise_seq_heatmap(my_numpy_array, size):
    for i in range(size):
        for j in range(size):
            X = Fasta[i].seq
            Y = Fasta[j].seq
            my_numpy_array[i,j] = int(pairwise2.align.globalxx(X, Y, score_only=True))
    return my_numpy_array
My_alignment_Scores = pairwise_seq_heatmap(alignments_score, size)
